===from:Dallas Crowley
===email:kcrowley@nwiowa.com
===institution:AC-T CSD
===date:Sun Mar 29 11:49:58 1998
===subject:Assignment 4, Part 2
===message:BT sprays have been used for around 40 years as an effective method of pest control.  It only seems natural that the next step in pest control would be to change the genetic makeup of the crops themselves.  Scientists accomplished this with BT corn.  BT corn has many advantages as well as disadvantages.<P>
The most obvious advantage is the controlling of the European Corn Borer (ECB).  There are also several less obvious advantages.  Because it's a natural pesticide, it has a much lower cost to the enviornment.  Farmers get bigger yields, and soil strain is decreased.  Although the seed costs more, farmers are able to save money because they don't have to put chemicals on the corn, and at the end of the season, they have a bigger yield resulting in more money for the farmer.<P>
But even with all these advantages, there are still several disadvantages.  By using the BT corn, it will eventually make the use of the BT spray non-effective, and with the BT spray's ability to kill ALL ECB (because they are not able to develop resistence that can be passed on to offspring), this is a very decided disadvantage.  This leads to the biggest disadvantage of the genetically engineered BT corn--the ECB is able to build up a resistence to the BT corn and subsequently pass that resistence on to future generations of ECB.  This trait would encourage the ECB that is resistent to the BT corn to survive, and after several generations, this population of resistent pests would be greater causing the BT corn to lose effectiveness.<P>
In order to counteract this effect, scientists say farmers would need to plant some non-BT corn as a haven for some of the ECB.  BT resistence has been found to be a recessive trait, and if we can maintain a population of non-resistent ECB to mate with the BT-resistent ECB, we will maintain future generations as non-resistent populations.  This haven would need to be close enough to the BT corn to ensure that the two populations (the resistent and the non-resistent) would be likely to breed and have non-resistent offspring, yet it needs to be far enough away that there are in fact two distinct populations.  If this were to happen, it would reduce the population of resistant ECB while maintaining many of the advantages of the BT corn.<P>
But, this raises another disadvantage.  History has shown that most farmers tend to do the most economically expedient thing of the moment (plant all BT corn) while ignoring the future disadvantages (BT-resistent ECB).  There will be a decided immediate cost disadvantage of planting two seperate crops--the BT corn, and the non-BT corn to function as a haven.  Becuase of this extra cost, fewer farmers are likely to want to do this, and in order for the BT corn to be successful, it is necessary for the farmers to take the responsibility on themselves.  If this haven is not established and maintained effectively, we will soon breed future generations of BT-resistent ECB.<P>
To me, the most important aspect is maintaining a low cost to the environment.  I believe that if there was a sure way to enforce all farmers to use BT corn "properly," then it would be a good, useful way to protect corn.  But, because there is no way to make sure all farmers will follow this plan and establish appropriate havens, I'm afraid we will see a future generation of BT-resistent ECB.  I think that we should just abandon the BT corn and allow the farmers who wish to use BT to continue using BT sprays which are proven effective without the disadvantage of develping resistent generations.<P>
=========yorg=========
