===message:Last year a new type of plant was introduced into the commercial market place. A farmer couldn’t tell the difference from an standard corn plant and this new type of corn plant. He may have noticed ( if he planted the Bt-corn) that his yields were a little higher. On the average 40 million tons of corn around the world never make it to market simply because of a little bug called the European Corn Boar.  This new type of plant I've mentioned, Bt-corn, addresses this problem head on by simply killing the ECB. The Bt-toxin kills the ECB by Dissolving the intestinal wall of the ECB and causing the little bugs to die of starvation. So this solves the problem of the ECB in theory. unfortunately the issue is much more complex. Some would like to think that this new type of corn is a waste of money. That it is will only lead to resistant ECB in a few years. That the Bt toxin is harmful to humans. Some of these allegations may be true, but then again, we don’t really know. As to the problem of development of resistance, it is very important to realize that the Bt-toxin has been used in agriculture as a spray for half a century.  So if you ask me the ECB has had ample opportunity to display resistance. Now, I'm not saying the ECB will not eventually become resistant. I’m just saying it may take longer than three growing seasons as some have said.  I would recommend that the EPA keep a close watch on the Bt-corn and the ECB.  They have systems to keep resistance from happening and it would be a good idea for a watchful eye.  As for the Bt-toxin harming humans, I think this is a scary point. Once again I refer to the issue that the Bt-toxin has been used for half a century. Not only that but the levels of the Bt-toxin in plants is   20% lower than the spray used per acre.  The only attack i have yet to address is that of the value of Bt-corn. Well if corn prices stay as high as they have been in the last few seasons every bushel counts.  Farmers may very well pay a premium price in the beginning to reap greater rewards at harvest time. For every argument only time will tell, and the fact remains the Bt-corn is out there and people are using. I just hope that a constant vigilance is kept to make sure everything is working as planned.
