===subject:Part 1 and 2
===message:This web site has information about the introduction of specialty corn (white and high-oil) with the Bt toxin gene:<P>
http://www.nk.com/infosilo/news/btwhite.html<P>

Part 2<P>
Bacillus thuringiensis is a soil organism that produce toxins that kill many pests that threaten our plants.  The toxin is ingested by insect larave.  Inside the intestines, the crystalline toxin rips up and paralyzes the digestive tract.  Depending on the variety of insect and toxin used, death occurs between twelve hours to five days after ingestion.<P>
Scientists have succeeded in making corn plants with the gene that produces the Bt toxin.  These plants make their own pesticides and are far more resistant to insect attacks, especially from the European corn borer.  Tests have shown that even under low infestation levels (one or fewer borers per plant) the Bt corn outproduces normal corn by six bushels per acre.  Under higher infestation levels (more than three borers per plant), the benefits are even greater.  The Bt plants produce 19 bushels per acre more than normal corn plants.<P>
The Bt corn also has a higher resistance to disease.  This is because the corn borer pests usually eat holes in leaves which leaves (HA! I made a pun!)the plant more succeptible to fungal and disease infections.<P>
All these new advantages are great and ecologically sound, but (as usual) there is a serious draw back.  According to many articles (and a biochemistry professor I listened to once), the corn borers can develop resistance to the toxin in plants.  This could wipe out the whole Bt corn idea.  Not only would it render the transgenic plants useless, it would make the spray Bt pesticides less effective too.  I think this is an issue that scientists should proceed with with caution.  I believe that more testing needs to be done before anyone takes any big steps.
=========yorg=========
===from:Rohit Ramaswamy
===email:rohitr@worldnet.att.net
===date:Sun Mar 29 17:57:02 1998
===subject:Assignment IV - part 2
===message:It is difficult to answer the question of whether the Bt corn technology should be widely adopted without looking at the cost and benefit data, which I couldn’t find on the web. The following discussion is based on information compiled from various web sites dealing with pest control.
<P>
The general consensus appears to be that the Bt technology is very effective at controlling corn borer larvae, and no major side effects are reported or anticipated. There are therefore clear benefits to using Bt corn. However, we need to consider the cost side as well.
<P>
The first question is whether the use of Bt corn is appropriate as a pest management device in a given year. A computer model developed by David Onsted at the University of Illinois at Urbana (see the website referenced in Part 1 of this exercise) shows that in the years where ECB populations are not at economic levels, traditional hybrids outperform Bt corn. The "economic injury level" is the population density of the pest (e.g. ECB larvae per plant) at which the potential loss of crop yield economically justifies the cost of treatment (see Larry Pedigo’s paper at www.ent.agri.umn.edu/academics/classes/ipm/chapters/pedigo.htm for more information on this topic). Clearly, therefore, the judgment about the use of Bt corn in a given year depends on whether the projection population density of ECB larvae is high enough to justify the extra cost of Bt corn. 
<P>
Given that the decision to use Bt corn has been made in a given year, the next question is to ascertain the amount of corn to be used. Onsted’s computer model also shows that if 100% of the corn acreage was planted with Bt corn, the ECB larvae would develop resistance to the Bt toxin in one year ! Onsted’s recommendation is that no more than 80% of the acreage be planted with Bt corn, and that that 20% non Bt corn should always be planted in strips next to the Bt corn so that susceptible corn borers can survive and mate with resistant corn borers. The model indicates that this will increase the resistance to 20 years. So this appears to be a natural limit on the usage of Bt corn.
<P>
In summary, therefore, it seems that rather than using Bt corn as the only means of ECB control, a combination of approaches may be desirable. In any year, the choice whether to use Bt corn should be based on the forecast of the larval population density. This forecast value depends not only on genetics and ecology, but also on the intervention strategies adopted in the past - the forecasting model therefore needs to be a dynamic time series model that is updated every year with actual data. I don’t know if such a model exists for the ECB, but population models are common in biology, so I assume that one has been developed for the ECB as well.
<P>
A hybrid strategy  does not imply that we should use pesticides; an integrated pest management approach focusing on biological solutions is more desirable, since pesticides will invariably prove to be an expensive option if the cost of externalities (bad environmental effects) resulting from pesticide use is included in the cost calculation. A website at www.nysaes.cornell.edu describes the breeding of small stingless moths that act as parasites in ECB eggs - maybe this approach can be combined with Bt corn.
<P>
 
 

=========yorg=========
===from:Bill Rockey
===email:brockey@iastate.edu
===institution:ISU
===date:Sun Mar 29 20:20:22 1998
===subject:Part 2
===message:	The production of genetically engineered crops is an explosive issue in agriculture today, particularly in Europe where the farming of genetically altered crops such as BT corn and Roundup Ready soybeans have been banned.  Farmers in the United States are attracted to such products by their high yields and low production costs while environmentalists are concerned that the genetically altered plants could cost consumers dearly down the road.  BT corn, for example, yields twenty bushels more per acre than traditional hybrids, not to mention the savings from not having to spray.  (Tobin, 1997).  Environmentalists are concerned that the use of BT corn could create new strains of ampicillin-resistant bacteria since the BT sequence contains a promoter for the ampicillin resistance gene which could be picked up by bacteria in animals’ and humans’ digestive tracts.  Furthermore, there is a concern that the widespread production of the crop will create a BT-resistant population of corn borers, and that the process of genetic manipulation may somehow decrease the nutritional value of the corn.  Europeans are upset that the U.S. is attempting to foist a new product upon them without providing an alternative since BT corn is not separated from traditional varieties in storehouses.  (Fagan, 1997) <P>
	My opinion on the subject is that BT corn production should be allowed if the farmer decides he can profitably market the corn domestically.  The economic advantages are certainly great, and by planting small plots of non-BT corn, the corn borer resistance problem could be combated.  Laboratory tests could be conducted to evaluate the ampicillin-resistance problem.  If it were shown that an outbreak of ampicillin-resistant bacteria were occurring, the situation would have to be reevaluated.  <P>

Fagan, John.  Importation of Ciba-Geigy's Bt Maize Is Scientifically Indefensible.
http://www.netlink.de/gen/BTCorn.htm. April 1997.  <P>

Tobin, Bernard.  Farm & Country. http://www.agpub.on.ca/text/jan97/cover.htm. Jan. 1997.   

