===message:In the BT-toxin treatment I see immediate short term advantages for individual farmers. After all, who in their right mind would not want to grow all of the corn they possibly could for their money. However, looking through a wider viewpoint we can look at the overall less money for their corn. The lower amounts of money received by farmers for their corn could result from a flood of excess grain in the markets. This often happens in todays market with just a good growing season, the supply exceeds the demand. In the future with a growing world population we may need to utilize this and all other genetic engineering tools to produce as much grain as possible. Now is not the time in my opinion, the market could not stand it.
Another important point to consider would be the resistance  the corn bores could acquire to resist the BT-Toxin, many other times we have come up with pesticides which work against insects but very rarely does a resistant population not soon follow.
Other important issues are social one
