===subject:Parts 2 & 3
===message:Researches have genetically modified corn so that it produces the protein of a soilbacterium in its leaves stalk and pollen.  This protein is called “Bt-toxin” and is producedby Bacillus thuringiensis.  This helps the plant to protect itself from the European cornborer.<p>There are some benefits to this new technology, but these benefits may not be long lasting. Developers of Bt-toxin have admitted that the use of these plants may hasten the evolutionof Bt-toxin resistant insects.  This new technology may be beneficial in the short term, butits use may hinder crops in the long run.  Bt-toxin has been used externally as a naturalpesticide for many crops.  If the use of Bt-toxin containing plants hastens the resistance ofinsects this will cause a problem for these growers, and we may find that we need toreturn to pesticides that are not as environmentally friendly.  I believe before thistechnology is widely used that there should be more extensive research to prevent thisresistance.<p>Reply to Bt corn part 2 by Lori Applegate<p>I agree that because Bt-toxin has been already used ECB will eventually be resistant inparts of the country, and eventually everywhere.  I also feel that this technology shouldhave only been applied when scientists were sure that they could prevent this.  Because ofthe use that has already occurred there will some day be resistant ECB.<p>
